subject: RE: [junit] JUnit Time output
msgSnippet: Hi, Dennis. I remember seeing your first question a week or two ago. If you didn t get any replies that suited you, it may mean that nobody knows the answer
messageBody:
Hi, Dennis. I remember seeing your first question a week or two ago. If
you didn't get any replies that suited you, it may mean that nobody
knows the answer offhand without looking at the source code. Which
reminds me, the source code to JUnit is really easy to read. Why don't
you look it over and find out for yourself? The code doesn't lie.


Todd.


> -----Original Message-----
> From: junit@yahoogroups.com [mailto:junit@yahoogroups.com] On
> Behalf Of Dennis
> Sent: Friday, July 13, 2007 6:42 AM
> To: junit@yahoogroups.com
> Subject: [junit] JUnit Time output
>
> Hello Everybpdy,
>
> This is my second attempt at posting to this group.
> I am interested in determining if the time values generated by JUnit
> 3.8 are suitable for use in benchmarking the unit under test.
>
> We have experimentally determined that the setUp() times are
> included in the time parameter. We are wondering of the
> tearDown() time is similary included?
>
> JUnit 4.3 looks very nice, and we are also wondering if the
> use of the @BeforeClass/@AfterClass Annotations will prevent
> the setUp/tearDown times being included.
>
> This seems like a suitable question and it is not covered in
> the FAQ, which was last modified in 2002.
>
> Thanks all
